│ DWARF operations take a ULEB128 or SLEB128 encoded immediate │
│ value. The constant `4704496199548239085565` is a 128-bit    │
│ value, and it is too large to be encoded as a standard       │
│ ULEB128/SLEB128 immediate within the DWARF-5 specification,  │
│ which typically limits these to 64 bits.                     │
│                                                              │
│ The `visitConstant` function in `LoopStrengthReduce.cpp` has │
│ a check: `if (C->getBitWidth() > 64) return;`. This check    │
│ correctly identifies that the 128-bit constant cannot be     │
│ handled and simply returns without adding any operations to  │
│ the `LocationOps` vector.                                    │
│                                                              │
│ Consequently, when `visitAddRecExpr` finishes, the           │
│ `LocationOps` vector is empty because neither the visit to   │
│ the IV (which is the base and doesn't emit ops itself) nor   │
│ the visit to the large constant added any operations. This   │
│ empty vector is then passed to `appendToVectors`, triggering │
│ the assertion failure.                                       │
│                                                              │
│ The fundamental problem is that the debug information        │
│ salvaging mechanism in LSR does not support affine           │
│ expressions with constant offsets that are larger than 64    │
│ bits.                                                        │
│                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to make `visitAddRecExpr` aware that its          │
│ recursive calls might fail to generate any DWARF operations. │
│ If a recursive call on an operand (like the large constant)  │
│ results in no new operations being added, it means that      │
│ operand could not be represented. In this case,              │
│ `visitAddRecExpr` should also fail by clearing any partial   │
│ results and returning, signaling that a valid DWARF          │
│ expression cannot be constructed for the whole               │
│ `SCEVAddRecExpr`.                                            │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopStrengthReduce.cpp      │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopStrengthReduce.cpp      │
│ @@ -6598,6 +6598,12 @@                                       │
│      // Visit the operand.                                   │
│      unsigned Before = LocationOps.size();                   │
│      visit(Operand);                                         │
│ +    if (Before == LocationOps.size()) {                     │
│ +      // We were unable to represent the operand, so we are │
│ unable to represent                                          │
│ +      // the sum.                                           │
│ +      LocationOps.clear();                                  │
│ +      return;                                               │
│ +    }                                                       │
│    }                                                         │
│                                                              │
│    // Add on the step.                                       │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ This change is placed within the loop in `visitAddRecExpr`.  │
│ After visiting an operand, it checks if any new operations   │
│ were added to `LocationOps`. If not, it means the operand    │
│ could not be encoded (e.g., a >64-bit constant). The         │
│ function then clears `LocationOps` to discard any partial    │
│ expression and returns, effectively propagating the failure  │
│ up the call stack. This prevents the `appendToVectors`       │
│ function from being called with an invalid empty expression. │
│                                                              │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                            │
│                                                              │
│ The proposed edit fixes the crash by ensuring that the       │
│ failure to represent a large constant in a SCEV expression   │
│ is handled gracefully. By checking the result of the         │
│ recursive `visit` call inside `visitAddRecExpr`, we can      │
│ detect when an operand cannot be encoded into a DWARF        │
│ expression. This prevents the construction of an invalid,    │
│ empty expression and avoids the subsequent assertion         │
│ failure. The `dbg.value` for the variable with the large     │
│ offset will not be salvaged, which is the correct behavior   │
│ given the limitations of DWARF expression encoding for large │
│ constants.                                                   │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------              │
